Optimization studies were carried out to improve the stability of the 
communication between the ESP32-CAM and the Python application. During the 
initial tests, it was observed that the video stream occasionally disconnected, 
requiring the connection to be re-established. To address this issue, the image 
acquisition mechanism was redesigned to automatically reconnect whenever the 
connection was lost.

The buffering mechanism used for processing the MJPEG stream over HTTP was also 
improved to increase reliability. Problems caused by incomplete data packets were 
minimized, and exception handling was added to prevent the application from terminating 
unexpectedly during connection failures. Instead, the application was able to recover 
automatically by reconnecting to the camera stream.

After implementing these improvements, the system was tested again. The MediaPipe-based 
hand detection algorithm and the virtual piano application were executed simultaneously 
using the real-time video stream from the ESP32-CAM. Compared with previous tests, a more 
stable and reliable video stream was achieved. Based on the obtained results, further 
optimization and the implementation of multi-finger support were planned for the next 
stage of the project.
